**Definition**
Component styling in React refers to applying CSS to individual components so each UI block has its own look and behavior.

**Types**

* **Inline Styling**
* **CSS Stylesheets**
* **CSS Modules**
* **Styled Components** (CSS-in-JS)
* **Tailwind / utility classes**

**Working**
React allows each component to include its own styling file or style object. Styles can be scoped (CSS Modules), global (normal CSS), or component-bound (styled-components). This keeps UI consistent and modular.

**Diagrams (text)**

```
Component
 ├── JSX
 ├── Logic
 └── Styles (CSS/Module/Inline)
```

**Advantages**

* Clean, modular UI
* Scoped styles prevent conflicts
* Multiple styling options
* Easier maintenance in large apps

**Disadvantages**

* Too many styling methods can confuse structure
* CSS-in-JS may increase overhead
* Inline styles lack full CSS features

**Examples**

**1. Inline Styling:**

```jsx
const box = { color: "blue", padding: "10px" };
return <div style={box}>Hello</div>;
```

**2. CSS File:**

```css
/* App.css */
.title { color: red; }
```

```jsx
<h1 className="title">React App</h1>
```

**3. CSS Modules:**

```css
/* Button.module.css */
.btn { background: green; }
```

```jsx
import styles from './Button.module.css';
<button className={styles.btn}>Click</button>
```

**4. Styled Components:**

```jsx
import styled from "styled-components";
const Btn = styled.button`background: purple;`;
```

**Applications**

* Theming
* UI components
* Dashboards
* Reusable styled widgets
